SIMPLE: personable
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Personable
<hw>Per"son*a*ble</hw> <pr>(p⟦etil⟧r"s⟦ucr⟧n*⟦adot⟧*b'l)</pr>,
<pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having a well-formed body, or person;
graceful; comely; of good appearance; presentable; <as>as, a
<ex>personable</ex> man or woman</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wise, warlike, <qex>personable</qex>, courteous, and kind.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The king, . . . so visited with sickness, was not
<qex>personable</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>E. Hall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Enabled to maintain
pleas in court.</def> <au>Cowell.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Having capacity
to take anything granted.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>personableness</ent>⟦br⟧
